{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a29fb336-a93b-45cf-8a3c-85cf62720c45","content":"Here are **3 evaluation performance anti-patterns** in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Deeply chained `<Import>` files\n`EvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props`\n\nEach nested import forces MSBuild to open, parse, and evaluate another XML file. A 3-level chain is mild, but this pattern scales poorly. **Prefer flattening imports** or using the SDK's built-in `Directory.Build.props` convention.\n\n### 2. File I/O via property function during evaluation\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nThis calls `System.IO.File.ReadAllText` **every time the project is evaluated** (design-time builds in IDEs, restores, etc.). File I/O in property functions is one of the most expensive evaluation-time operations. Move this to a **target** that runs only during build, or use an MSBuild task instead.\n\n### 3. Overly broad recursive wildcard glob\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` forces MSBuild to walk the **entire directory tree** during evaluation to expand the glob. This gets worse as the repo grows. **Narrow the glob** to specific extensions or directories (e.g., `**\\*.txt`) to reduce filesystem enumeration.\n\n---\n\n**Severity ranking:** #2 (file read) > #3 (recursive glob) > #1 (import depth). The file read and broad glob are the biggest offenders since they perform I/O on every single evaluation pass.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2f4323ec-45ba-488e-936b-d0fdb62d46fc","outputTokens":409},"id":"452edbd4-a47c-4f6f-b6a8-e47d18e4bfb9","timestamp":"2026-04-05T01:09:48.306Z","parentId":"be7ad663-2e18-4ae5-97de-509faba5f39c"}
